{"title_page": "Timmy Trumpet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- Individual -->\n| image            = Timmy Trumpet Interview at Airbeat One 2019.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Timmy Trumpet after an interview at Airbeat One 2019\n| image_size       = 220px\n| landscape        = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Timothy Jude Smith\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1982|6|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = Sydney, Australia\n| instrument       = Trumpet, digital trumpet, piano, keyboard\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Electro house]]\n*[[House music|House]]\n*[[Big room house|Big room]]\n*[[Psytrance]]\n*[[Hardstyle]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Musician, DJ, songwriter, record producer\n| years_active     = 2005\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Spinnin' Records|Spinnin']]\n*[[Revealed Recordings|Revealed]]\n*[[Ministry of Sound Australia|Ministry of Sound]],\n*[[Monstercat]]\n*[[Dim Mak Records|Dim Mak]]\n*[[Armada Music|Armada]]\n*[[Ultra Music]]\n}}\n| website          = {{Official Website|www.timmytrumpet.com}}\n| module           = \n| Wife             = Anett Tomcs\u00e1nyi\n}}\n\n'''Timothy Jude Smith''' (born 9 June 1982),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/timmy-trumpet-mn0002020453/biography?1585287900313 |title=Timmy Trumpet - Biography & History |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2020-03-27}}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Timmy Trumpet''', is an Australian musician, DJ, songwriter and record producer. He has become known internationally for playing the trumpet live and making use of jazz elements in the realm of global dance music.\n\nTimmy Trumpet's breakthrough single \"[[Freaks (Timmy Trumpet and Savage song)|Freaks]]\" with New Zealand rapper [[Savage (rapper)|Savage]] was certified gold by the [[RIAA]], six times platinum by [[ARIA]], and triple platinum by [[Recorded Music NZ]]. Timmy Trumpet is currently ranked the number 13 DJ in the world, according to the ''[[DJ Mag]]'' Top 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djmag.com/top100djs|title=DJ Mag Top 100 2019 Results |work=djmag.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2019, Timmy Trumpet became the first trumpet player to perform in Zero Gravity, a project partnership between the [[European Space Agency]] and BigCityBeats.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.thenocturnaltimes.com/bigcitybeats-world-club-dome-historically-touches-down-with-exclusive-zero-gravity-party/|title= BigCityBeats' WORLD CLUB DOME Historically Touches Down with Exclusive Zero Gravity Party|last=Graves|first=Ciarra|date=2019-04-04|work=The Nocturnal Times|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://themusicnetwork.com/it-was-like-no-other-experience-ive-ever-had-before-timmy-trumpet-plays-dj-set-in-zero-gravity/|title=\"It was like no other experience I've ever had before\": Timmy Trumpet plays DJ set in zero gravity|date=2019-04-04|work=Music Network|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTimothy Jude Smith was born in Sydney, Australia. Timothy started playing the trumpet at an early age, taught by his father. At thirteen, Timothy was named 'Young Musician of the Year' before being granted a full scholarship to the [[Sydney Conservatorium of Music|Conservatorium of Music]], where he was tutored by Anthony Heinrich of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]]. Within two years he secured a position as the leading solo trumpet player in the Australian All-Star Stage Band.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.xsnoize.com/interview-timmy-trumpet-no-one-parties-like-the-irish-the-crowds-in-belfast-are-always-crazy/|title= INTERVIEW: Timmy Trumpet \u2013 \"No one parties like the Irish! The crowds in Belfast are always crazy\"|last=Millar|first=Mark|date=2019-08-14|work=XS Noize|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2010\u20132015: Early career in Australia===\nTimothy adopted the stage name Timmy Trumpet and began performing as a trumpeter alongside Australian DJ duo the [[Stafford Brothers]] at Australian nightclubs and music festivals. Timothy then taught himself how to DJ and began playing solo shows billed as Timmy Trumpet, incorporating live trumpet into his DJ sets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moshtix.com.au/v2/event/the-stafford-brothers-and-timmy-trumpet/47782|title=The Met presents the Stafford Brothers and Timmy Trumpet|work=moshtix.com.au|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYDv1dyMDN0|title= \"Future Music Festival 2011\" Stafford Brothers ft Timmy Trumpet|via=YouTube|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QAXoXX1b4vM|title=\"Future Music Festival 2012\" Stafford Brothers ft Timmy Trumpet |work=youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nTimmy Trumpet signed early music releases to Australian record labels OneLove, Central Station and Hussle Recordings, and produced various mix compilations for Ministry of Sound Australia which included national promotional tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.discogs.com/artist/1142687-Timmy-Trumpet|title=Timmy Trumpet Discography|work=discogs.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/ministry-of-sound-sessions-9-20120801-23f63.html|title=Ministry of Sound: Sessions 9|last=Fry|first=Douglas|date=2012-08-02|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.sydneyunleashed.com/ministry-of-sound-sessions-10/|title=Ministry of Sound: Sessions 10|work=Sydney Unleashed|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Timmy Trumpet was selected as the support act for [[Stevie Wonder]] at The Star Casino in Sydney\u2019s grand opening.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.pedestrian.tv/music/stars-converge-on-the-star-for-stevie-wonder/|title= Stars Converge On The Star For Stevie Wonder|date=2011-10-26|work=Pedestrian|access-date=2012-01-10}}</ref> Timmy also appeared as himself in a reoccurring role on [[The Stafford Brothers]], a reality TV show originally broadcast on [[FOX8]].\n\nBetween 2012 and 2015, Timmy had a number of singles hit number one on the ARIA Club Chart, the first being a collaboration titled 'Sassafras', with Melbourne DJ Chardy. Sassafras was the number two track on the ARIA end of year Charts - Top 50 Club Tracks of 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-club-chart-2012.htm|title= ARIA Charts - End Of Year Charts - Top 50 Club Tracks 2012|work= aria.com.au |access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> 'The Buzz', a collaboration with [[New World Sound]] reached number one on [[Beatport]] in addition to reaching number one on the ARIA Club Chart. The Buzz was also used in the [[Dirty Grandpa]] official TV trailer.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://spinninrecords.com/synchs/The-Buzz-Dirty-Grandpa-Trailer/|title= 'The Buzz' by Timmy Trumpet & New World Sound in Dirty Grandpa Trailer|work= spinninrecords.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> \"Freaks\", a collaboration with Savage reached number one of ARIA Australian Singles, Dance and Club Charts and has since been accredited six times platinum in Australia. Freaks is the highest selling single of all time on Ministry of Sound Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.umusicpub.com/au/Artists/T/Timmy-Trumpet.aspx|title= Universal Music Publishing Group Biograpghy|work= umusicpub.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nTimmy Trumpet was voted the number one DJ in Australia at the 2015 inthemix Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://ibisplay.com/discover/the-2015-inthemix-awards-results-are-in/|title= The 2015 inthemix Awards Results Are In |last=Cunningham|first=Katie|date=2015-06-25|work=Ibis Play|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132016: \"Freaks\" and international attention ===\n\"[[Freaks (Timmy Trumpet and Savage song)|Freaks]]\" is the twelfth single release for Timmy Trumpet. The track garnered international success charting in Australia, New Zealand, Hungary, Poland, Belgium, France and the Netherlands and has sold more than one million copies worldwide and has been streamed online over five hundred million times. \"Freaks\" reached number three on the ARIA chart and number one in New Zealand.\n\n\"Freaks\" features in the Hollywood TV shows and films ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]'', ''[[Collide (film)|Collide]]'', ''[[Teen Wolf (2011 TV series)|Teen Wolf]]'', ''[[American Ultra]]'' and ''[[Training Day (TV series)|Training Day]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.tunefind.com/artist/timmy-trumpet|title= Timmy Trumpet music featured in movies and TV shows|work= tunefind.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n\"Freaks\" debuted on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' emerging artists + [[Twitter]] chart at number nine when a [[Vine (service)|Vine]] titled \u2018When mama isn\u2019t home\u2019 went viral. The video features Brisbane father and son Russ and Toby Bauer. The father plays Freaks on a trombone whilst his son slams the oven door repeatedly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/case-study-timmy-trumpets-dual-us-chart-debut/|title= Case Study: Timmy Trumpet's dual US chart debut |last=Reid|first=Poppy|date=2015-10-27|work=Music Network|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> As of October 2015, the Vine received over 26 million loops, 201,800 likes and 158,200 Re-Vines. On 18 November 2015, Russ and Toby Bauer remade the viral video live on Australian national TV on Nine Network's ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' where Timmy Trumpet surprised them, turning up halfway through the performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hdX_thqMCe4|title= Timmy Trumpet joins Oven Boy for a TODAY Show jam|work= youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nBy 2015, Timmy Trumpet was gaining recognition within the music industry overseas and started writing and producing music with international artists. \"Toca\", the first of a series of international collaborations, was with Guatemalan-American DJ and producer, [[Carnage (DJ)|Carnage]] and Indian-American DJ and producer [[KSHMR]]. \"Toca\" is a [[Big room house|Big room]] rework of the classical  [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] composition \"[[Toccata and Fugue in D minor, BWV 565|Toccata and Fugue in D minor]]\". \"Toca\" was released on 26 June 2015 on [[Ultra Music]]. The track has since become a trademark of Timmy Trumpet's live performances, utilizing elements of the original orchestral introduction and playing live trumpet.\n\nIn 2016, Timmy Trumpet released three singles on dutch dance label [[Spinnin' Records]]. The first release \"Psy or Die\" was circulated around the DJ scene without anyone knowing who had authored the unreleased track at the time, and it was played at festivals and nightclubs by [[Armin Van Buuren]], [[W&W]], [[Blasterjaxx]], [[Nervo (DJs)|NERVO]] and [[Andrew Rayel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7430932/carnage-timmy-trumpet-psy-or-die|title= Carnage & Timmy Trumpet Release 'Psy or Die,' and You Might Have Heard it Already|last=Bein|first=Kat|date=2016-07-07|work= billboard.com |access-date=2019-10-19|language=en-US}}</ref> It was later revealed when released that \"Psy or Die\" was by Timmy Trumpet and Carnage and the track was popular on the European dance music festival scene that summer. On 27 September 2016 Spinnin Records released \"Party Till We Die\" by [[MAKJ]] and Timmy Trumpet featuring rock artist and motivational speaker [[Andrew W.K.]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/hear-andrew-w-k-s-aggressive-edm-debut-party-til-we-die-103648/|title= Hear Andrew W.K.\u2019s Aggressive EDM Debut \u2018Party Til We Die\u2019|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|date=2016-09-27|work= rollingstone.com|access-date=2019-10-19|language=en-US}}</ref> Timmy's debut solo single released on Spinnin' titled \"Oracle\" reached number one on Beatport, and has received more than 150 million online streams as of October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=__TvPr_Wtvc|title=Timmy Trumpet - Oracle (Official Music Video)|work= youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://open.spotify.com/album/2QJkwrO6mHtWT4HZbIq1mj|title=Timmy Trumpet - Oracle on Spotify|work=Spotify|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: Global music festivals===\n\nIn 2017, Timmy Trumpet made his main stage debut at[[Tomorrowland (festival)|Tomorrowland]] in Boom, Belgium. His performance is the most streamed DJ set of all time on Tomorrowland's official YouTube channel, and as of October 2019 has received twenty-two million views.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EccF9ISUgEQ&t|title= Tomorrowland Belgium 2017|via=YouTube|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2017 and 2018, Timmy Trumpet became a fixture at dance music festivals all over the world, playing main stage sets at [[Parookaville]], [[Electric Love]], Creamfields, Airbeat One, and many more.\n\nTimmy Trumpet collaborated with [[Hardwell]] on the track \"The Underground\" which was released on Revealed Recordings. He also collaborated with DJ and producers Vini Vici on \"100\" and Blasterjaxx on \"Narco\".\n\nOn 21 June 2018, Timmy Trumpet sold-out [[Ormeau Park]] in Belfast, Northern Ireland, selling 15,000 tickets.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/belsonic-day-4-timmy-trumpet-sells-out-ormeau-park-belfast-photos-37037876.html|title= Timmy Trumpet sells out Ormeau Park|work= belfasttelegraph.co.uk |access-date=2019-10-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2019: World tour and zero gravity===\n\nOn 25 March 2019, Timmy Trumpet joined a host of celebrities on the BigCityBeats World Club Dome \"Zero Gravity 2.0\". A specially converted A310 aircraft, usually used by the European Space Agency for training astronauts and performing scientific experiments in microgravity and other levels of reduced gravity, took off from Frankfurt Airport. The aircraft engaged in a series of parabolic flights which caused the passengers to experience a total of six minutes of true weightlessness.\n\nOn 18 April 2019, Timmy Trumpet announced a 60 date World at our Feet world tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BwYtbydhvMy/|title=Timmy Trumpet World Tour Announcement|work= instagram.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The coinciding title single \"World at our Feet\" was released on 10 May, along with an animated lyric video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fvOCPf7fPaE|title=Timmy Trumpet - World At Our Feet (Official Lyric Video)|work= youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The tour included main stage headlining performances at 31 festivals across the Europe, North America, South America and Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.bandsintown.com/a/445444-timmy-trumpet|title=Timmy Trumpet on Bandsintown|work= bandsintown.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Timmy hosted his own stages at Tomorrowland and [[Creamfields]]. Timmy made his main stage debut at [[Electric Daisy Carnival]] in Las Vegas on 19 May,<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://edm.com/events/edc-las-vegas-2019-lineup|title= EDC Las Vegas Announces Full Lineup for 2019 Edition|work= edm.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> and later was announced as a headliner of Electric Daisy Carnival in Orlando, South Korea, and China.\n\nTimmy began a VLOG series on YouTube chronicling his life on tour. The first episode follows his experiences at Electric Daisy Carnival in Las Vegas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLB5ki38vOvIKUgxgVpWtEyhU7ZT2cyFs0|title=Timmy Trumpet on YouTube|via=YouTube|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nTimmy Trumpet is renowned for his energetic live performances and use of pyrotechnics on stage. Timmy plays mixed platform electronic music, blending many sub-genres together, playing music at various speeds, and incorporating live trumpet solos over custom edits. Timmy's DJ sets predominantly feature his own original tracks, collaborations and remixes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1001tracklists.com/dj/timmytrumpet/index.html|title= Timmy Trumpet Tracklists Overview|work= 1001tracklists.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nTimmy has released music in a number of sub-genres of electronic music including House, Electro, Bounce, Hardstyle, Psy-trance, Big Room, Funk, Hip Hop and Pop.\n\nTimmy has cited [[Daft Punk]] as early inspiration to start experimenting with electronic dance music. In an interview with Belfast Telegraph, Timmy said: \"I was a trumpeter before I was a DJ, I would play alongside songs I heard on the radio. I remember playing to Daft Punk for the first time. That's when I realised there might be something to this trumpet/EDM thing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/qa-timmy-trumpet-on-selling-out-belsonic-i-wish-the-rest-of-the-world-partied-as-hard-as-belfast-37034648.html|title= Q&A: Timmy Trumpet on selling out Belsonic - 'I wish the rest of the world partied as hard as Belfast'|date=2018-06-21|work=XS Noize|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Timmy Trumpet discography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trumpet, Timmy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian DJs]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sydney]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Monstercat artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century trumpeters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- Individual -->\n| image            = Timmy Trumpet Interview at Airbeat One 2019.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Timmy Trumpet after an interview at Airbeat One 2019\n| image_size       = 220px\n| landscape        = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Timothy Jude Smith\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1982|6|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = Sydney, Australia\n| instrument       = Trumpet, digital trumpet, piano\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Electro house]]\n*[[House music|House]]\n*[[Big room house|Big room]]\n*[[Psytrance]]\n*[[Hardstyle]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Musician, DJ, songwriter, record producer\n| years_active     = 2005\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Spinnin' Records|Spinnin']]\n*[[Revealed Recordings|Revealed]]\n*[[Ministry of Sound Australia|Ministry of Sound]],\n*[[Monstercat]]\n*[[Dim Mak Records|Dim Mak]]\n*[[Armada Music|Armada]]\n*[[Ultra Music]]\n}}\n| website          = {{Official Website|www.timmytrumpet.com}}\n| module           = \n| Wife             = Anett Tomcs\u00e1nyi\n}}\n\n'''Timothy Jude Smith''' (born 9 June 1982),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/timmy-trumpet-mn0002020453/biography?1585287900313 |title=Timmy Trumpet - Biography & History |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2020-03-27}}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Timmy Trumpet''', is an Australian musician, DJ, songwriter and record producer. He has become known internationally for playing the trumpet live and making use of jazz elements in the realm of global dance music.\n\nTimmy Trumpet's breakthrough single \"[[Freaks (Timmy Trumpet and Savage song)|Freaks]]\" with New Zealand rapper [[Savage (rapper)|Savage]] was certified gold by the [[RIAA]], six times platinum by [[ARIA]], and triple platinum by [[Recorded Music NZ]]. Timmy Trumpet is currently ranked the number 13 DJ in the world, according to the ''[[DJ Mag]]'' Top 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djmag.com/top100djs|title=DJ Mag Top 100 2019 Results |work=djmag.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2019, Timmy Trumpet became the first trumpet player to perform in Zero Gravity, a project partnership between the [[European Space Agency]] and BigCityBeats.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.thenocturnaltimes.com/bigcitybeats-world-club-dome-historically-touches-down-with-exclusive-zero-gravity-party/|title= BigCityBeats' WORLD CLUB DOME Historically Touches Down with Exclusive Zero Gravity Party|last=Graves|first=Ciarra|date=2019-04-04|work=The Nocturnal Times|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://themusicnetwork.com/it-was-like-no-other-experience-ive-ever-had-before-timmy-trumpet-plays-dj-set-in-zero-gravity/|title=\"It was like no other experience I've ever had before\": Timmy Trumpet plays DJ set in zero gravity|date=2019-04-04|work=Music Network|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTimothy Jude Smith was born in Sydney, Australia. Timothy started playing the trumpet at an early age, taught by his father. At thirteen, Timothy was named 'Young Musician of the Year' before being granted a full scholarship to the [[Sydney Conservatorium of Music|Conservatorium of Music]], where he was tutored by Anthony Heinrich of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]]. Within two years he secured a position as the leading solo trumpet player in the Australian All-Star Stage Band.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.xsnoize.com/interview-timmy-trumpet-no-one-parties-like-the-irish-the-crowds-in-belfast-are-always-crazy/|title= INTERVIEW: Timmy Trumpet \u2013 \"No one parties like the Irish! The crowds in Belfast are always crazy\"|last=Millar|first=Mark|date=2019-08-14|work=XS Noize|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2010\u20132015: Early career in Australia===\nTimothy adopted the stage name Timmy Trumpet and began performing as a trumpeter alongside Australian DJ duo the [[Stafford Brothers]] at Australian nightclubs and music festivals. Timothy then taught himself how to DJ and began playing solo shows billed as Timmy Trumpet, incorporating live trumpet into his DJ sets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moshtix.com.au/v2/event/the-stafford-brothers-and-timmy-trumpet/47782|title=The Met presents the Stafford Brothers and Timmy Trumpet|work=moshtix.com.au|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uYDv1dyMDN0|title= \"Future Music Festival 2011\" Stafford Brothers ft Timmy Trumpet|via=YouTube|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QAXoXX1b4vM|title=\"Future Music Festival 2012\" Stafford Brothers ft Timmy Trumpet |work=youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nTimmy Trumpet signed early music releases to Australian record labels OneLove, Central Station and Hussle Recordings, and produced various mix compilations for Ministry of Sound Australia which included national promotional tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.discogs.com/artist/1142687-Timmy-Trumpet|title=Timmy Trumpet Discography|work=discogs.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/ministry-of-sound-sessions-9-20120801-23f63.html|title=Ministry of Sound: Sessions 9|last=Fry|first=Douglas|date=2012-08-02|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.sydneyunleashed.com/ministry-of-sound-sessions-10/|title=Ministry of Sound: Sessions 10|work=Sydney Unleashed|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Timmy Trumpet was selected as the support act for [[Stevie Wonder]] at The Star Casino in Sydney\u2019s grand opening.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.pedestrian.tv/music/stars-converge-on-the-star-for-stevie-wonder/|title= Stars Converge On The Star For Stevie Wonder|date=2011-10-26|work=Pedestrian|access-date=2012-01-10}}</ref> Timmy also appeared as himself in a reoccurring role on [[The Stafford Brothers]], a reality TV show originally broadcast on [[FOX8]].\n\nBetween 2012 and 2015, Timmy had a number of singles hit number one on the ARIA Club Chart, the first being a collaboration titled 'Sassafras', with Melbourne DJ Chardy. Sassafras was the number two track on the ARIA end of year Charts - Top 50 Club Tracks of 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-club-chart-2012.htm|title= ARIA Charts - End Of Year Charts - Top 50 Club Tracks 2012|work= aria.com.au |access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> 'The Buzz', a collaboration with [[New World Sound]] reached number one on [[Beatport]] in addition to reaching number one on the ARIA Club Chart. The Buzz was also used in the [[Dirty Grandpa]] official TV trailer.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://spinninrecords.com/synchs/The-Buzz-Dirty-Grandpa-Trailer/|title= 'The Buzz' by Timmy Trumpet & New World Sound in Dirty Grandpa Trailer|work= spinninrecords.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> \"Freaks\", a collaboration with Savage reached number one of ARIA Australian Singles, Dance and Club Charts and has since been accredited six times platinum in Australia. Freaks is the highest selling single of all time on Ministry of Sound Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.umusicpub.com/au/Artists/T/Timmy-Trumpet.aspx|title= Universal Music Publishing Group Biograpghy|work= umusicpub.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nTimmy Trumpet was voted the number one DJ in Australia at the 2015 inthemix Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://ibisplay.com/discover/the-2015-inthemix-awards-results-are-in/|title= The 2015 inthemix Awards Results Are In |last=Cunningham|first=Katie|date=2015-06-25|work=Ibis Play|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132016: \"Freaks\" and international attention ===\n\"[[Freaks (Timmy Trumpet and Savage song)|Freaks]]\" is the twelfth single release for Timmy Trumpet. The track garnered international success charting in Australia, New Zealand, Hungary, Poland, Belgium, France and the Netherlands and has sold more than one million copies worldwide and has been streamed online over five hundred million times. \"Freaks\" reached number three on the ARIA chart and number one in New Zealand.\n\n\"Freaks\" features in the Hollywood TV shows and films ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]'', ''[[Collide (film)|Collide]]'', ''[[Teen Wolf (2011 TV series)|Teen Wolf]]'', ''[[American Ultra]]'' and ''[[Training Day (TV series)|Training Day]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.tunefind.com/artist/timmy-trumpet|title= Timmy Trumpet music featured in movies and TV shows|work= tunefind.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n\"Freaks\" debuted on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' emerging artists + [[Twitter]] chart at number nine when a [[Vine (service)|Vine]] titled \u2018When mama isn\u2019t home\u2019 went viral. The video features Brisbane father and son Russ and Toby Bauer. The father plays Freaks on a trombone whilst his son slams the oven door repeatedly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/case-study-timmy-trumpets-dual-us-chart-debut/|title= Case Study: Timmy Trumpet's dual US chart debut |last=Reid|first=Poppy|date=2015-10-27|work=Music Network|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> As of October 2015, the Vine received over 26 million loops, 201,800 likes and 158,200 Re-Vines. On 18 November 2015, Russ and Toby Bauer remade the viral video live on Australian national TV on Nine Network's ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' where Timmy Trumpet surprised them, turning up halfway through the performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hdX_thqMCe4|title= Timmy Trumpet joins Oven Boy for a TODAY Show jam|work= youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nBy 2015, Timmy Trumpet was gaining recognition within the music industry overseas and started writing and producing music with international artists. \"Toca\", the first of a series of international collaborations, was with Guatemalan-American DJ and producer, [[Carnage (DJ)|Carnage]] and Indian-American DJ and producer [[KSHMR]]. \"Toca\" is a [[Big room house|Big room]] rework of the classical  [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] composition \"[[Toccata and Fugue in D minor, BWV 565|Toccata and Fugue in D minor]]\". \"Toca\" was released on 26 June 2015 on [[Ultra Music]]. The track has since become a trademark of Timmy Trumpet's live performances, utilizing elements of the original orchestral introduction and playing live trumpet.\n\nIn 2016, Timmy Trumpet released three singles on dutch dance label [[Spinnin' Records]]. The first release \"Psy or Die\" was circulated around the DJ scene without anyone knowing who had authored the unreleased track at the time, and it was played at festivals and nightclubs by [[Armin Van Buuren]], [[W&W]], [[Blasterjaxx]], [[Nervo (DJs)|NERVO]] and [[Andrew Rayel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7430932/carnage-timmy-trumpet-psy-or-die|title= Carnage & Timmy Trumpet Release 'Psy or Die,' and You Might Have Heard it Already|last=Bein|first=Kat|date=2016-07-07|work= billboard.com |access-date=2019-10-19|language=en-US}}</ref> It was later revealed when released that \"Psy or Die\" was by Timmy Trumpet and Carnage and the track was popular on the European dance music festival scene that summer. On 27 September 2016 Spinnin Records released \"Party Till We Die\" by [[MAKJ]] and Timmy Trumpet featuring rock artist and motivational speaker [[Andrew W.K.]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/hear-andrew-w-k-s-aggressive-edm-debut-party-til-we-die-103648/|title= Hear Andrew W.K.\u2019s Aggressive EDM Debut \u2018Party Til We Die\u2019|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|date=2016-09-27|work= rollingstone.com|access-date=2019-10-19|language=en-US}}</ref> Timmy's debut solo single released on Spinnin' titled \"Oracle\" reached number one on Beatport, and has received more than 150 million online streams as of October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=__TvPr_Wtvc|title=Timmy Trumpet - Oracle (Official Music Video)|work= youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://open.spotify.com/album/2QJkwrO6mHtWT4HZbIq1mj|title=Timmy Trumpet - Oracle on Spotify|work=Spotify|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: Global music festivals===\n\nIn 2017, Timmy Trumpet made his main stage debut at[[Tomorrowland (festival)|Tomorrowland]] in Boom, Belgium. His performance is the most streamed DJ set of all time on Tomorrowland's official YouTube channel, and as of October 2019 has received twenty-two million views.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EccF9ISUgEQ&t|title= Tomorrowland Belgium 2017|via=YouTube|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2017 and 2018, Timmy Trumpet became a fixture at dance music festivals all over the world, playing main stage sets at [[Parookaville]], [[Electric Love]], Creamfields, Airbeat One, and many more.\n\nTimmy Trumpet collaborated with [[Hardwell]] on the track \"The Underground\" which was released on Revealed Recordings. He also collaborated with DJ and producers Vini Vici on \"100\" and Blasterjaxx on \"Narco\".\n\nOn 21 June 2018, Timmy Trumpet sold-out [[Ormeau Park]] in Belfast, Northern Ireland, selling 15,000 tickets.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/belsonic-day-4-timmy-trumpet-sells-out-ormeau-park-belfast-photos-37037876.html|title= Timmy Trumpet sells out Ormeau Park|work= belfasttelegraph.co.uk |access-date=2019-10-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2019: World tour and zero gravity===\n\nOn 25 March 2019, Timmy Trumpet joined a host of celebrities on the BigCityBeats World Club Dome \"Zero Gravity 2.0\". A specially converted A310 aircraft, usually used by the European Space Agency for training astronauts and performing scientific experiments in microgravity and other levels of reduced gravity, took off from Frankfurt Airport. The aircraft engaged in a series of parabolic flights which caused the passengers to experience a total of six minutes of true weightlessness.\n\nOn 18 April 2019, Timmy Trumpet announced a 60 date World at our Feet world tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BwYtbydhvMy/|title=Timmy Trumpet World Tour Announcement|work= instagram.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The coinciding title single \"World at our Feet\" was released on 10 May, along with an animated lyric video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fvOCPf7fPaE|title=Timmy Trumpet - World At Our Feet (Official Lyric Video)|work= youtube.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The tour included main stage headlining performances at 31 festivals across the Europe, North America, South America and Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.bandsintown.com/a/445444-timmy-trumpet|title=Timmy Trumpet on Bandsintown|work= bandsintown.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Timmy hosted his own stages at Tomorrowland and [[Creamfields]]. Timmy made his main stage debut at [[Electric Daisy Carnival]] in Las Vegas on 19 May,<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://edm.com/events/edc-las-vegas-2019-lineup|title= EDC Las Vegas Announces Full Lineup for 2019 Edition|work= edm.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> and later was announced as a headliner of Electric Daisy Carnival in Orlando, South Korea, and China.\n\nTimmy began a VLOG series on YouTube chronicling his life on tour. The first episode follows his experiences at Electric Daisy Carnival in Las Vegas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLB5ki38vOvIKUgxgVpWtEyhU7ZT2cyFs0|title=Timmy Trumpet on YouTube|via=YouTube|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\nTimmy Trumpet is renowned for his energetic live performances and use of pyrotechnics on stage. Timmy plays mixed platform electronic music, blending many sub-genres together, playing music at various speeds, and incorporating live trumpet solos over custom edits. Timmy's DJ sets predominantly feature his own original tracks, collaborations and remixes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1001tracklists.com/dj/timmytrumpet/index.html|title= Timmy Trumpet Tracklists Overview|work= 1001tracklists.com|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nTimmy has released music in a number of sub-genres of electronic music including House, Electro, Bounce, Hardstyle, Psy-trance, Big Room, Funk, Hip Hop and Pop.\n\nTimmy has cited [[Daft Punk]] as early inspiration to start experimenting with electronic dance music. In an interview with Belfast Telegraph, Timmy said: \"I was a trumpeter before I was a DJ, I would play alongside songs I heard on the radio. I remember playing to Daft Punk for the first time. That's when I realised there might be something to this trumpet/EDM thing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/qa-timmy-trumpet-on-selling-out-belsonic-i-wish-the-rest-of-the-world-partied-as-hard-as-belfast-37034648.html|title= Q&A: Timmy Trumpet on selling out Belsonic - 'I wish the rest of the world partied as hard as Belfast'|date=2018-06-21|work=XS Noize|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Timmy Trumpet discography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trumpet, Timmy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian DJs]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sydney]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Monstercat artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century trumpeters]]\n", "name_user": "StrongDonnie0511", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timmy_Trumpet"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Shaffer (writer)", "text_new": "{{For|the U.S. intelligence officer|Anthony Shaffer (intelligence officer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Anthony Shaffer\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n|birth_name     = Anthony Joshua Shaffer\n| birth_date    = 15 May 1926\n| birth_place   = [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], UK\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|2001|11|7|1926|5|15}}\n| death_place   = Chelsea and Westminster Hospital, [[London]], UK\n| resting_place = [[Highgate Cemetery]], London\n| occupation    = Playwright, screenwriter, novelist, barrister, advertising executive\n|spouse=Henrietta J. Glaskie (1954\u2013195?)<br />Carolyn Soley ()<br />[[Diane Cilento]] (1985\u2013his death)\n| children      = 2\n}}\n'''Anthony Joshua Shaffer''' (15 May 1926{{spaced ndash}}7 November 2001<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Paul |title=Anthony Shaffer, 75, Author Of Long-Running 'Sleuth,' Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/12/theater/anthony-shaffer-75-author-of-long-running-sleuth-dies.html |accessdate=3 January 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 November 2001 |pages=F7}}</ref>) was an English playwright, screenwriter, novelist, barrister and advertising executive.\n\n==Early life==\nShaffer was born to a [[Jew]]ish family in [[Liverpool]], the son of Reka (n\u00e9e Fredman) and Jack Shaffer, who was an [[estate agent]] with his wife's family.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/95/Anthony-Shaffer.html Film Reference bio]</ref><ref>[http://www.forward.com/articles/14301/ www.forward.com]</ref> He was the identical twin brother of writer and dramatist [[Peter Shaffer]], and they had another brother, Brian. He graduated with a law degree from [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].\n\n==Career==\nShaffer worked as a barrister and advertising copywriter before becoming a full-time writer.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/nov/07/news.nigelfountain Obituary in [[The Guardian]], 7 november 2001]</ref>\n\nShaffer's most notable work was the play ''[[Sleuth (play)|Sleuth]]'' (1970), which he adapted for the [[Sleuth (1972 film)|film version]] which starred [[Laurence Olivier]] and [[Michael Caine]], and was nominated for an [[Academy Award]]. He received [[Edgar Award]]s from the [[Mystery Writers of America]] for both versions: for Best Play in 1971, and Best Screenplay in 1973.\n\nHis other major screenplays include the [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock]] thriller ''[[Frenzy]]'' (1972) and the British cult thriller ''[[The Wicker Man (1973 film)|The Wicker Man]]'' (1973) with whose director, [[Robin Hardy (film director)|Robin Hardy]], Shaffer had previously set up a television production company Hardy, Shaffer & Associates.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Allan|title=Inside the Wicker Man: How Not to Make a Cult Classic|date=2012|publisher=Birlinn|location=New York|isbn=9780857902177}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShaffer was married three times\u2014to Henrietta Glaskie, Carolyn Soley (with whom he had two children, Claudia and Cressida), and [[Australia]]n actress [[Diane Cilento]].\n\nShaffer met Cilento in 1973, when she appeared in ''The Wicker Man''. He moved to Australia in 1975 and married Cilento in 1985. Together they built a house (''The Castle'') and a theater (''The Karnak Playhouse''). Shaffer was legally domiciled in Australia (where he owned land and a restaurant, paid taxes and voted in elections), although he did maintain a flat in [[London]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1453901/Shaffers-lover-fails-in-battle-over-his-estate.html \"Shaffer's lover fails in battle over his estate\"]. Article of 10 February 2004 by Sean O'Neill in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''</ref>\n\nIn the last years of his life Shaffer had an extramarital relationship with Marie Josette \"JoJo\" Capece-Minutolo when in London. Cilento did not accompany Shaffer to England but remained in Australia. After Shaffer's death, Capece-Minutolo made a claim on his estate in the British High Court, arguing that Shaffer had intended to divorce Cilento and marry her and that he had given her an engagement ring. The Shaffer estate argued that Shaffer had no desire to end his marriage to Cilento. The British judge found that despite Shaffer's being in \"an intimate and loving relationship\" with Capece in London,  Shaffer (and his estate) were not legally domiciled in the United Kingdom at the time of his death and that therefore Capece-Minutolo had no legal claims on his estate, other than any bequest in Shaffer's will (which had been changed in 1999).<ref>{{cite news |title=Playwright's family fight off mistress's claim to share legacy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/feb/10/arts.artsnews |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 February 2004 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Peter Antony==\nHe co-wrote three detective novels with his playwright brother Peter Shaffer under the pseudonym ''Peter Antony''.\n*''The Woman in the Wardrobe'' (1951)\n*''[[How Doth the Little Crocodile?]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Withered Murder]]''  (1955)\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n*''The Woman in the Wardrobe: a lighthearted detective story'' (1951) - co-written with Peter Shaffer, published under the pseudonym \"Peter Antony\"\n*''[[How Doth The Little Crocodile]]'' (1952) - co-written with Peter Shaffer, as by \"Peter Antony\"\n*''[[Withered Murder]]'' (1955) - co-written with Peter Shaffer, as by A. & P. Shaffer\n*''Absolution''  (1979) \u2013 based on Shaffer's screenplay for the [[Absolution (1978 film)|1978 film]]\n*''[[The Wicker Man (novel)|The Wicker Man]]'' (1978) \u2013 co-written with [[Robin Hardy (film director)|Robin Hardy]], based on Shaffer's screenplay\n\n===Plays===\n*''The Savage Parade'' (1963; 1966; later revised as ''This Savage Parade'', 1987)\n*''[[Sleuth (play)|Sleuth]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Murderer (play)|Murderer]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Whodunnit (play)|Whodunnit]]'' (1977; originally called ''The Case of the Oily Levantine'')\n*''Widow's Weeds or For Years I Couldn't Wear My Black'' (1986); 1977 world premiere in Brisbane, Queensland, by the Queensland Theatre Company)'' \n*''The Thing in the Wheelchair'' (2001)\n\n===Memoir===\n*''So What Did You Expect?'' (2001)\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Screenplays===\n*''[[Mr. Forbush and the Penguins]]''  (1971) \u2013 a.k.a. ''Cry of the Penguins''\n*''[[Frenzy]]''  (1972)\n*''[[Sleuth (1972 film)|Sleuth]]''  (1972)\n*''[[The Wicker Man (1973 film)|The Wicker Man]]''  (1973)\n*''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974) (uncredited)<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Paul|title=Anthony Shaffer, 75, Author Of Long-Running 'Sleuth,' Dies|date=12 November 2001|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/12/theater/anthony-shaffer-75-author-of-long-running-sleuth-dies.html|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url =https://books.google.com/?id=THpkAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=anthony+shaffer+murder+on+the+orient+express#v=onepage&q=anthony%20shaffer%20murder%20on%20the%20orient%20express&f=false|title =Jolly Good Detecting: Humor in English Crime Fiction of the Golden Age| isbn = 9781476613963 | author1 =Shaw| first1 =Bruce|year=2013}}</ref>\n*''[[Death on the Nile (1978 film)|Death on the Nile]]''  (1978)\n*''[[Absolution (1978 film)|Absolution]]''  (1978)\n*''[[Evil Under the Sun (1982 film)|Evil Under the Sun]]''  (1982)\n*''[[Appointment with Death (film)|Appointment with Death]]''  (1988) \u2013 co-screenplay\n*''[[Sommersby]]''  (1993) \u2013 co-story\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0787289|Anthony Shaffer}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904034527/http://www.anthonyshaffer.co.uk/ The Life & Work of Anthony Shaffer]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1361694/Anthony-Shaffer.html telegraph.co.uk]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,3604,589481,00.html Obituary] in ''[[The Guardian]]'' (8 November 2001)\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/12/theater/anthony-shaffer-75-author-of-long-running-sleuth-dies.html nytimes.com]\n*[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=27967873&PIpi=11496891 Photo of Shaffer's grave at] [[Findagrave]]\n\n{{Anthony Shaffer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shaffer, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Identical twins]]\n[[Category:Jewish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Twin people from England]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Burials at Highgate Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the U.S. intelligence officer|Anthony Shaffer (intelligence officer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Anthony Shaffer\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n|birth_name     = Anthony Joshua Shaffer\n| birth_date    = 15 May 1926\n| birth_place   = [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], UK\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|2001|11|7|1926|5|15}}\n| death_place   = Chelsea and Westminster Hospital, [[London]], UK\n| resting_place = [[Highgate Cemetery]], London\n| occupation    = Playwright, screenwriter, novelist, barrister, advertising executive\n|spouse=Henrietta J. Glaskie (1954\u2013195?)<br />Carolyn Soley ()<br />[[Diane Cilento]] (1985\u2013his death)\n| children      = 2\n}}\n'''Anthony Joshua Shaffer''' (15 May 1926{{spaced ndash}}7 November 2001<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Paul |title=Anthony Shaffer, 75, Author O