e pseudonym ''Peter Antony''.\n*''The Woman in the Wardrobe'' (1951)\n*''[[How Doth the Little Crocodile?]]'' (1952)\n*''[[Withered Murder]]''  (1955)\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n*''The Woman in the Wardrobe: a lighthearted detective story'' (1951) - co-written with Peter Shaffer, published under the pseudonym \"Peter Antony\"\n*''[[How Doth The Little Crocodile]]'' (1952) - co-written with Peter Shaffer, as by \"Peter Antony\"\n*''[[Withered Murder]]'' (1955) - co-written with Peter Shaffer, as by A. & P. Shaffer\n*''Absolution''  (1979) \u2013 based on Shaffer's screenplay for the [[Absolution (1978 film)|1978 film]]\n*''[[The Wicker Man (novel)|The Wicker Man]]'' (1978) \u2013 co-written with [[Robin Hardy (film director)|Robin Hardy]], based on Shaffer's screenplay\n\n===Plays===\n*''The Savage Parade'' (1963; 1966; later revised as ''This Savage Parade'', 1987)\n*''[[Sleuth (play)|Sleuth]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Murderer (play)|Murderer]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Whodunnit (play)|Whodunnit]]'' (1977; originally called ''The Case of the Oily Levantine'')\n*''Widow's Weeds or For Years I Couldn't Wear My Black'' (1986); 1977 world premiere in Brisbane, Queensland, by the Queensland Theatre Company)'' \n*''The Thing in the Wheelchair'' (2001)\n\n===Memoir===\n*''So What Did You Expect?'' (2001)\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Screenplays===\n*''[[Mr. Forbush and the Penguins]]''  (1971) \u2013 a.k.a. ''Cry of the Penguins''\n*''[[Frenzy]]''  (1972)\n*''[[Sleuth (1972 film)|Sleuth]]''  (1972)\n*''[[The Wicker Man (1973 film)|The Wicker Man]]''  (1973)\n*''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974) (uncredited)<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Paul|title=Anthony Shaffer, 75, Author Of Long-Running 'Sleuth,' Dies|date=12 November 2001|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/12/theater/anthony-shaffer-75-author-of-long-running-sleuth-dies.html|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url =https://books.google.com/?id=THpkAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=anthony+shaffer+murder+on+the+orient+express#v=onepage&q=anthony%20shaffer%20murder%20on%20the%20orient%20express&f=false|title =Jolly Good Detecting: Humor in English Crime Fiction of the Golden Age| isbn = 9781476613963 | author1 =Shaw| first1 =Bruce|year=2013}}</ref>\n*''[[Death on the Nile (1978 film)|Death on the Nile]]''  (1978)\n*''[[Absolution (1978 film)|Absolution]]''  (1978)\n*''[[Evil Under the Sun (1982 film)|Evil Under the Sun]]''  (1982)\n*''[[Appointment with Death (film)|Appointment with Death]]''  (1988) \u2013 co-screenplay\n*''[[Sommersby]]''  (1993) \u2013 co-story\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0787289|Anthony Shaffer}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110904034527/http://www.anthonyshaffer.co.uk/ The Life & Work of Anthony Shaffer]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1361694/Anthony-Shaffer.html telegraph.co.uk]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,3604,589481,00.html Obituary] in ''[[The Guardian]]'' (8 November 2001)\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/12/theater/anthony-shaffer-75-author-of-long-running-sleuth-dies.html nytimes.com]\n*[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=27967873&PIpi=11496891 Photo of Shaffer's grave at] [[Findagrave]]\n\n{{Anthony Shaffer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shaffer, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Identical twins]]\n[[Category:Jewish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Twin people from England]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Burials at Highgate Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "StrongDonnie0511", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Shaffer_(writer)"}
{"title_page": "Gideon (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Gideon\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kenny Rogers]]\n| cover      = Gideon_Kenny.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1980\n| recorded   = 1980\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 34:05\n| label      = [[United Artists Group]]\n| producer   = [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]] and Kenny Rogers\n| prev_title = [[Kenny (album)|Kenny]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Greatest Hits (1980 Kenny Rogers album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n}}\n\n'''''Gideon''''' is the [[Platinum record|platinum]]-selling ninth studio album by [[Kenny Rogers]]. Issued by [[United Artists Records]] in 1980, it hit #1 on the Country albums chart and #12 on the main [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] album chart. It includes the worldwide hit \"Don't Fall in Love with a Dreamer\" (a duet with [[Kim Carnes]], who co-wrote the entire album with her husband Dave Ellingson).\n\n''Gideon'' is a concept album about a Texas cowboy, and all the songs stick to this theme. The album is a look back at his life in retrospect. In the first song \"Gideon Tanner\", it is known that Gideon is dead. This and most of the other songs are sung from the point of view of the character himself.\n\nAlthough the album's only single release was \"Don't Fall in Love with a Dreamer\", the song \"Saying Goodbye\" was issued on the B-side to Rogers' top five hit single \"Love the World Away\".\n\n''Gideon'' reached No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Country charts in 1980.\n\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r93934|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{tracklist\n|all_writing = [[Kim Carnes]] and David M. Ellingson \n|title1= Goin' Home to the Rock\n|note1= intro\n|length1= 0:40\n|title2= Gideon Tanner\n|length2= 2:34\n|title3= No Good Texas Rounder\n|length3= 4:11\n|title4= [[Don't Fall in Love with a Dreamer]]\n|note4= with [[Kim Carnes]]\n|length4= 3:39\n|title5= The Buckeroos\n|length5= 3:16\n|title6= You Were a Good Friend\n|length6= 3:53\n|title7= Call Me Up (The Phone Is in the Cradle)\n|length7= 3:17\n|title8= These Chains\n|length8= 3:22\n|title9= Somebody Help Me\n|length9= 2:51\n|title10= One Place in the Night\n|length10= 2:59\n|title11= Sayin' Goodbye\n|length11= 3:25\n|title12= Goin' Home to the Rock\n|note12= reprise\n|length12= 0:58\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* Kenny Rogers \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]] \u2013 acoustic piano\n* Bill Cuomo \u2013 acoustic piano\n* Steve Glassmeyer \u2013 acoustic piano, backing vocals\n* Eugene Golden \u2013 acoustic piano, backing vocals\n* Edgar Struble \u2013 [[clavinet]], synthesizers, backing vocals, horn arrangements (7)\n* Randy Dorman \u2013 guitar\n* Patrick Harper \u2013 guitar\n* Billy Sanford \u2013 guitar, dobro\n* Chuck Jacobs \u2013 bass guitar\n* Bobby Daniels \u2013 drums, backing vocals\n* [[Jerry Carrigan]] \u2013 percussion\n* [[Bill Justis]] \u2013 string arrangements\n* [[The Sheldon Kurland Strings]] \u2013 strings\n* Lea Jane Berinati \u2013 backing vocals\n* [[Kim Carnes]] \u2013 backing vocals, lead vocals (4)\n* James Cason \u2013 backing vocals\n* David Ellingson \u2013 backing vocals\n* Wendy Suits \u2013 backing vocals\n* Dennis Wilson \u2013 backing vocals\n\n==Production==\n* Producers \u2013 Larry Butler and Kenny Rogers\n* Engineer \u2013 [[Billy Sherrill]]\n* Mixing \u2013 [[Bill Schnee]] \n* Recorded at [[Jack Clement|Jack Clement Recording Studios]] (Nashville, TN).\n* Masteted by [[Doug Sax]] at The Mastering Lab (Los Angeles, CA).\n* Art Direction \u2013 Bill Burks\n* Cover and Poster Photos \u2013 Ken Kragen\n* Back Cover Photo \u2013 [[Reid Miles]]\n* Management \u2013 Kragen & Company\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1980)\n! Peak position\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Top Country Albums\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' 200\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12\n|-\n| Australian ''([[Kent Music Report]])'' Albums\n| align=\"center\"| 31<ref>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St. Ives, N.S.W.|year=1993|edition=Illustrated|page=256|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|-\n| Canadian ''RPM'' Country Albums\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| Canadian ''RPM'' Top Albums\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.music.com/release/gideon/1/ Gideon album page at Music.com]\n*[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r93934|pure_url=yes}} Gideon album page at Allmusic]\n\n{{Kenny Rogers}}\n\n[[Category:1980 albums]]\n[[Category:Kenny Rogers albums]]\n[[Category:United Artists Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Larry Butler (producer)]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n\n\n{{1980s-country-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Gideon\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kenny Rogers]]\n| cover      = Gideon_Kenny.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1980\n| recorded   = 1980\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 34:05\n| label      = [[United Artists Group]]\n| producer   = [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]] and Kenny Rogers\n| prev_title = [[Kenny (album)|Kenny]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Greatest Hits (1980 Kenny Rogers album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n}}\n\n'''''Gideon''''' is the [[Platinum record|platinum]]-selling ninth studio album by [[Kenny Rogers]]. Issued by [[United Artists Records]] in 1980, it hit #1 on the Country albums chart and #12 on the main [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] album chart. It includes the worldwide hit \"Don't Fall in Love with a Dreamer\" (a duet with [[Kim Carnes]], who co-wrote the entire album with her husband Dave Ellingson).\n\n''Gideon'' is a concept album about a Texas cowboy, and all the songs stick to this theme. The album is a look back at his life in retrospect. In the first song \"Gideon Tanner\", it is known that Gideon is dead. This and most of the other songs are sung from the point of view of the character himself.\n\nAlthough the album's only single release was \"Don't Fall in Love with a Dreamer\", the song \"Saying Goodbye\" was issued on the B-side to Rogers' top five hit single \"Love the World Away\".\n\n''Gideon'' reached No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Country charts in 1980.\n\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r93934|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{tracklist\n|all_writing = [[Kim Carnes]] and David M. Ellingson \n|title1= Goin' Home to the Rock\n|note1= intro\n|length1= 0:40\n|title2= Gideon Tanner\n|length2= 2:34\n|title3= No Good Texas Rounder\n|length3= 4:11\n|title4= [[Don't Fall in Love with a Dreamer]]\n|note4= with [[Kim Carnes]]\n|length4= 3:39\n|title5= The Buckeroos\n|length5= 3:16\n|title6= You Were a Good Friend\n|length6= 3:53\n|title7= Call Me Up (The Phone Is in the Cradle)\n|length7= 3:17\n|title8= These Chains\n|length8= 3:22\n|title9= Somebody Help Me\n|length9= 2:51\n|title10= One Place in the Night\n|length10= 2:59\n|title11= Sayin' Goodbye\n|length11= 3:25\n|title12= Goin' Home to the Rock\n|note12= reprise\n|length12= 0:58\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* Kenny Rogers \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]] \u2013 acoustic piano\n* Bill Cuomo \u2013 acoustic piano\n* Steve Glassmeyer \u2013 acoustic piano, backing vocals\n* Eugene Golden \u2013 acoustic piano, backing vocals\n* Edgar Struble \u2013 [[clavinet]], synthesizers, backing vocals, horn arrangements (7)\n* Randy Dorman \u2013 guitar\n* Patrick Harper \u2013 guitar\n* Billy Sanford \u2013 guitar, dobro\n* Chuck Jacobs \u2013 bass guitar\n* Bobby Daniels \u2013 drums, backing vocals\n* [[Jerry Carrigan]] \u2013 percussion\n* [[Bill Justis]] \u2013 string arrangements\n* [[The Sheldon Kurland Strings]] \u2013 strings\n* Lea Jane Berinati \u2013 backing vocals\n* [[Kim Carnes]] \u2013 backing vocals, lead vocals (4)\n* James Cason \u2013 backing vocals\n* David Ellingson \u2013 backing vocals\n* Wendy Suits \u2013 backing vocals\n* Dennis Wilson \u2013 backing vocals\n\n==Production==\n* Producers \u2013 Larry Butler and Kenny Rogers\n* Engineer \u2013 [[Billy Sherrill]]\n* Mixing \u2013 [[Bill Schnee]] \n* Recorded at [[Jack Clement|Jack Clement Recording Studios]] (Nashville, TN).\n* Masteted by [[Doug Sax]] at The Mastering Lab (Los Angeles, CA).\n* Art Direction \u2013 Bill Burks\n* Cover and Poster Photos \u2013 Ken Kragen\n* Back Cover Photo \u2013 [[Reid Miles]]\n* Management \u2013 Kragen & Company\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1980)\n! Peak position\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Top Country Albums\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' 200\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12\n|-\n| Australian ''([[Kent Music Report]])'' Albums\n| align=\"center\"| 31<ref>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St. Ives, N.S.W.|year=1993|edition=Illustrated|page=256|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|-\n| Canadian ''RPM'' Country Albums\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| Canadian ''RPM'' Top Albums\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\n|}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.music.com/release/gideon/1/ Gideon album page at Music.com]\n*[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r93934|pure_url=yes}} Gideon album page at Allmusic]\n\n{{Kenny Rogers}}\n\n[[Category:1980 albums]]\n[[Category:Kenny Rogers albums]]\n[[Category:United Artists Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Larry Butler (producer)]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n\n\n{{1980s-country-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gideon_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Juliana Harkavy", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress writer and singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         = Juliana Harkavy, 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| caption       = Harkavy in 2017\n| name          = Juliana Harkavy\n| birth_name    = Juliana Jay Harkavy\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1985|1|1}}\n| birth_place   = New York City\n| occupation    = Actress, writer, musician\n| years_active  = 1996\u2013present\n| notable_works = ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]''\n| spouse        = {{married|Peter Christopher Kupchick|2014}}\n}}\n\n'''Juliana Jay Harkavy'''<ref name=marriage>{{cite web|url=https://www.fairfieldcitizenonline.com/news/article/Wedding-Kupchick-Harkavy-5748868.php|title=Wedding / Kupchick-Harkavy|publisher=\"Fairfield Citizen\"|date=September 11, 2014}}</ref> (born January 1, 1985) is an American actress, writer, and musician. She is known for portraying Rebecca in ''[[Dolphin Tale]]'', Jessie in ''[[Day One (2012 film)|To Write Love on her Arms]]'', and [[List of The Walking Dead (TV series) characters#Martinez's group|Alisha]] in the television series ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''.  Her roles include a starring role in the [[horror film]] ''[[Last Shift]]'', and a reprise of her role as Rebecca in ''[[Dolphin Tale 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2013/10/18/dolphin-tale-2-filming-underway-at-clearwater-aquarium/ |title='Dolphin Tale 2' filming underway at Clearwater Aquarium |publisher=On Location Vacations |date=October 18, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg |first=Matt |url=https://collider.com/renee-movie-image-set-photo/ |title=RENEE Movie Image and Set Photo |publisher=Collider |date=February 16, 2012 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/06/anthony-deblasi-directing-horror-pic-paymon/ |title=Anthony DiBlasi Directing Horror Pic \u2018Paymon\u2019 |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |date=June 28, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/photo/juliana-harkavy-the-los-angeles-premiere-of-dolphin-tale-at-the-mann_3518761 |title=Picture \u2013 Juliana Harkavy Los Angeles, California, Saturday 17th September 2011 &#124; Photo 2588460 |publisher=Contactmusic.com |date=September 17, 2011 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reneethemovie.com/cast.html |title=Meet The Cast |publisher=Reneethemovie.com |accessdate=August 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223432/http://www.reneethemovie.com/cast.html |archivedate=December 2, 2013 }}</ref> She was a series regular on [[The CW]] superhero series ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]'', portraying [[Dinah Drake (Arrowverse)|Dinah Drake / Black Canary]].<ref name=\"Crucible ep\">{{cite episode|title=Second Chances|series=Arrow|credits=Speed Weed & Sarah Tarkoff (writers) & Mark Bunting (director)|network=The CW|airdate=February 1, 2017|season=5|number=11}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarkavy was born in New York City. She is the daughter of Berta Carela and Michael Harkavy, who is the former Senior Vice president of [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Entertainment]] Worldwide Publishing, [[Kids' WB]] Music, and [[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Her professional acting career began when she was 10 years old.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Harkavy has described herself as \"a [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] [[Jew]]\", although her mother was born [[Catholic]].<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/JulianaHarkavy/status/512376226825371648</ref><ref>https://www.instagram.com/julianaharkavy/p/BSuKKOBjOhd/</ref> She also said that her paternal ancestors were from Russia and Hungary, whereas her maternal ancestors were from the Dominican Republic, Africa, and China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JulianaHarkavy/status/829135942556405760|title=That's right! That's mom's side. Pops is Russian/Hungarian |publisher=Twitter|date=February 7, 2017}}{{Primary source inline|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHarkavy trained at the [[Young Actors Space]] in [[Sherman Oaks, California]] for nine years. She attended her first year of high school at [[Le Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais de Los Angeles]], where she became fluent in French,{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} and did part of her schooling in the South of France. She earned her high school diploma from the [[Milken Community High School]] in Los Angeles, California.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}After high school, Harkavy attended The [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]], where she majored in Theater in the Sanford Meisner studio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3952890/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=ABCD|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHarkavy's first acting job was at age 10 in a commercial for the [[Fox Kids]] series ''[[Goosebumps (TV series)|Goosebumps]]'', based on the popular horror-book series.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Her first role in a major motion picture was an uncredited role in the 1995 version of ''[[A Little Princess (1995 film)|A Little Princess]]'', directed by [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nHarkavy starred in the 2011 film ''If You Only Knew'' about early-onset [[Alzheimer's Disease]]. She stars as Jessica Loren in the [[horror film]] ''[[Last Shift]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/news-article/character-poster-paymon |title=Chiller &#124; Scary Good |publisher=Fearnet.com |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Ryan|last=Turek |url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/174643-first-official-image-from-anthony-diblasis-paymon/ |title=First Official Image from Anthony DiBlasi's Paymon |publisher=Shock Till You Drop |date=June 25, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://horrorcultfilms.co.uk/2013/07/character-one-sheets-released-for-dread-directors-unique-sounding-chiller-paymon/ |title=Character one-sheets released for Dread director's unique sounding chiller \u2018Paymon\u2019 \" Horror Cult Films \u2013 Movie Reviews of Obscure, Weird, Strange, Horror and Cult Cinema |publisher=Horror Cult Films |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHarkavy starred in the 2010 short film ''[[Whatever Lola Wants (film)|Whatever Lola Wants]]''. Nominated for a Best Actress Award at the 2011 [[University of Miami]] Canes Film Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canesfilmfest.moonfruit.com/ |title=Canes Film Festival |accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\nHarkavy is the star in the short film ''The Lost Doll'' directed by James Walhberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rumbumstudios.com/uncategorized/the-lost-doll-short-film-co-produced-by-jim-wahlberg-and-rum-bum-film-hd-studios/  |title= The Lost Doll Short Film PSA Commercial| accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHarkavy plays Alisha, a survivor involved with the Governor on ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''. She appeared in two episodes: \"Dead Weight\" and \"Too Far Gone\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Dessner |first=Dina |url=http://geekleagueofamerica.com/2013/12/01/geek-league-interview-juliana-harkavy-alicia-on-the-walking-dead/ |title=Geek League Interview \u2013 Juliana Harvkavy, \"Alisha\" On 'The Walking Dead' |publisher=Geek League of America |date=December 1, 2013 |accessdate=August 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 she was cast in the [[Arrow (season 5)|fifth season]] of the [[The CW|CW]] show ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]'', in the recurring role of Detective Tina Boland,<ref>[http://tvline.com/2016/11/01/arrow-cast-detective-boland-juliana-harkavy/ \"TVLine Items:Arrow's New Detective\"] \"TVLine\". Retrieved December 28, 2016.</ref> whose true name is revealed to be [[Dinah Drake (Arrowverse)|Dinah Drake]], acting as the new [[Black Canary]].<ref name=\"Crucible ep\"/> She was promoted to series regular for the show's [[Arrow (season 6)|sixth season]], which began airing in the fall of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/arrow-rick-gonzalez-juliana-harkavy-wild-dog-black-canary-promoted-season-6-regulars-1202068856/|title=Arrow Ups Rick Gonzalaz & Juliana Harkavy To Season 6 Regulars|publisher=\"Deadline Hollywood\"|date=April 13, 2017|accessdate=May 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 19, 2014, she married Peter Christopher Kupchick (son of State Rep. [[Brenda Kupchick]] and Peter Kupchick).<ref name=marriage/>\n\nShe has lived in New York, [[New Mexico]], [[New Jersey]], California, Florida, and France.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nShe plays the piano, the guitar, and the flute.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n\n===Film===\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[A Little Princess (1995 film)|A Little Princess]]''\n| Girl in India\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Flushed''\n| Groupie\n| Short\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2006\n| ''Love is Blind''\n| Crystal\n|\n|-\n| ''[[My Super Ex-Girlfriend]]'' \n| Passerby\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Whatever Lola Wants''\n| Lola\n| Short movie, nominated for Best Actress Award at UM Canes film festival.\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2011\n| ''[[Dolphin Tale]]''\n| Rebecca\n| \n|-\n| ''If You Only Knew''\n| Louise\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''A Feeling from Within''\n| Stacey\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2013\n| ''Finding Joy''\n| Pretty Young Woman\n| \n|-\n| ''[[House of Bodies]]''\n| Tisha\n| \n|-\n| ''Marriage Material''\n| Madeline\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=2|2014\n| ''[[Dolphin Tale 2]]''\n| Rebecca\n|\n|- \n|''[[Last Shift]]''\n| Officer Jessica Loren\n| \n|-\n|2015 \n|''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]''\n|Jessie\n|Filmed in 2011, released in 2015\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"